"Implement the following plan:\n\n# Fix Two Cursor Bug Bot Comments on PR #554\n\n## Context\nTwo cursor[bot] comments from ~7 min ago flagged bugs introduced on this branch. Both are valid and straightforward to fix.\n\n## Bug 1: Stdin timeout in shared function affects all agents\n**File:** `cmd/entire/cli/agent/event.go` (lines 156-182)\n\n**Problem:** `ReadAndParseHookInput` added a 500ms timeout around `io.ReadAll`. The bot correctly notes that `io.ReadAll` doesn't return until EOF — so if an agent's hook caller writes data but takes >500ms to close the pipe (send EOF), the timeout fires and discards the data, returning `ErrEmptyHookInput`.\n\n**Fix:** Instead of timing out the entire `io.ReadAll`, read into a buffer with a deadline-aware approach. However, the simpler and more correct fix: use a **two-phase approach** — set a short timeout for the *first byte* to detect \"no data at all\" (Kiro's case), but once data starts arriving, wait longer for EOF.\n\nActually, the simplest correct fix: read with a buffer in a loop using a deadline on the reader if it supports it. But since `stdin` is just an `io.Reader`, the cleanest approach is:\n- Keep the goroutine + channel pattern\n- But after timeout, check if any data was partially read — not possible with `io.ReadAll`\n\n**Simplest correct fix:** Use `bufio.Reader.Peek(1)` with the timeout to detect empty stdin, then do `io.ReadAll` without timeout once we know data exists:\n\n```go\nfunc ReadAndParseHookInput[T any](stdin io.Reader) (*T, error) {\n    br := bufio.NewReader(stdin)\n\n    // Phase 1: Check if any data is available (with timeout for Kiro's open-pipe case)\n    ch := make(chan readResult, 1)\n    go func() {\n        _, err := br.Peek(1)\n        ch <- readResult{err: err}\n    }()\n\n    select {\n    case res := <-ch:\n        if res.err != nil {\n            if res.err == io.EOF {\n                return nil, ErrEmptyHookInput\n            }\n            return nil, fmt.Errorf(\"failed to read hook input: %w\", res.err)\n        }\n    case <-time.After(stdinReadTimeout):\n        return nil, ErrEmptyHookInput\n    }\n\n    // Phase 2: Data available — read all of it (no timeout, wait for EOF)\n    data, err := io.ReadAll(br)\n    if err != nil {\n        return nil, fmt.Errorf(\"failed to read hook input: %w\", err)\n    }\n    if len(data) == 0 {\n        return nil, ErrEmptyHookInput\n    }\n\n    var result T\n    if err := json.Unmarshal(data, &result); err != nil {\n        return nil, fmt.Errorf(\"failed to parse hook input: %w\", err)\n    }\n    return &result, nil\n}\n```\n\nThis fixes the bug because: once we know data exists (Peek succeeds), we let `io.ReadAll` run to completion without a timeout. The timeout only applies to detecting \"no data at all\" — Kiro's open-pipe scenario.\n\n## Bug 2: Silent empty data masks errors for non-Kiro agents\n**File:** `cmd/entire/cli/strategy/manual_commit_condensation.go` (lines 130-136)\n\n**Problem:** When `TranscriptPath == \"\"` and no shadow branch exists, the code creates empty `ExtractedSessionData{}`. This is correct for Kiro (deferred SQLite persistence) but would silently swallow errors for other agents.\n\n**Fix:** Guard with agent type check. The `agent` package is already imported and `state.AgentType` is available:\n\n```go\nif state.TranscriptPath == \"\" {\n    if state.AgentType != agent.AgentTypeKiro {\n        return nil, fmt.Errorf(\"shadow branch not found and no live transcript available for agent %s\", state.AgentType)\n    }\n    // Kiro-specific: deferred SQLite persistence...\n    sessionData = &ExtractedSessionData{}\n}\n```\n\n## Files to modify\n1. `cmd/entire/cli/agent/event.go` — Two-phase stdin read (Peek with timeout, then ReadAll without timeout)\n2. `cmd/entire/cli/strategy/manual_commit_condensation.go` — Add agent type guard on empty session data\n\n## Verification\n```bash\nmise run fmt && mise run lint && mise run test:ci\n```\n\n\nIf you need specific details from be